<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
    <a href="/backlog/2564-adopt-spec-based-programming-across-the-constellation-schema/">#2564</a> proposes a
    strategic direction: move the constellation toward <strong>spec-based (spec-driven) programming</strong> —
    the <strong>spec is a human-owned artifact</strong>, and the <strong>implementation under it is
    agent-clearable</strong> when a conformance suite stays green and an independent review agrees the spec is
    preserved. Two things were already ratified in discussion: the spec is a <strong>schema / executable
    contract, not prose</strong> (only that makes "did the spec change?" a deterministic yes/no), and the model
    is <strong>human-gates-spec / agent-implements</strong>. This survey grounds the four open forks in how the
    wider ecosystem actually does spec-driven development for AI agents. Full adversarially-verified report:
    <code>reports/2026-07-18-spec-based-programming-deep-research.md</code>.
</p>

<h2>Verdict</h2>
<p>
    Spec-driven development for AI agents is <strong>real but immature</strong> — the field is
    <strong>&lt; 18 months old</strong> and essentially all current tooling sits at Fowler's
    <em>spec-first</em> rung (spec written, then discarded). A durable gate needs at least
    <em>spec-anchored</em> (kept + evolved), which no tool delivers out of the box. So adopting this means
    <strong>assembling</strong> the discipline — schema spec + contract tests + CI gate + authority tiers — not
    buying one mature tool. The binding constraint on AI-assisted dependability is
    <strong>specification discipline, not model capability</strong>: investing in the contract gate beats
    chasing a better generator.
</p>

<h2>The survey — load-bearing findings</h2>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Finding</th><th>Evidence</th><th>Implies for the constellation</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Prose SDD tools are not machine-diffable</strong></td>
            <td>GitHub Spec Kit, Amazon Kiro (EARS), Tessl are markdown generators; a prose diff cannot give a
                clean yes/no on "did the spec change?"</td>
            <td>Confirms schema-not-prose — do NOT adopt a prose formalism as the gate</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Schema-as-spec IS deterministically diffable</strong></td>
            <td>TypeSpec compiles one source to OpenAPI&nbsp;3.0 / JSON&nbsp;Schema&nbsp;2020-12 / Protobuf via
                reproducible emitters</td>
            <td>The formalism class the plan needs — and WE's intent/protocol JSON is already this shape</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>LLMs cannot author formal specs</strong></td>
            <td>TLA+ across 30 models / 2,730 runs: ≤26.6% syntactic, <strong>8.6% semantic</strong> correctness;
                a valid-parsing spec can still be behaviourally wrong</td>
            <td>Human-authors-spec / agent-implements is well-founded; don't force executable form on invariants
                that resist faithful formalization</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>A green suite proves "code matches spec", never "spec is right"</strong></td>
            <td>Specmatic fails the build on any deviation — but a wrong spec yields faithfully-wrong code</td>
            <td>Human on every SPEC change + an independent review agent are non-negotiable</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Drift is empirically widespread</strong></td>
            <td>55% of Node-RED nodes exceed their declared spec</td>
            <td>A <em>mechanical</em> drift gate beats trusting discipline</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Specmatic's central-contract-repository ≈ the constellation, 1:1</strong></td>
            <td>Contracts live in ONE repo (single source of truth); downstream repos REFERENCE and never OWN
                them; cross-boundary changes gate on a human PR + backward-compat check, plus a conformance
                suite in the consumer repos</td>
            <td>Maps WE&nbsp;(owns spec) → FUI/plateau&nbsp;(reference + implement); answers <em>where specs
                live</em> and <em>how to gate cross-boundary changes</em></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>The "Spec Growth Engine" already unifies #2563 + #2564</strong></td>
            <td>arXiv&nbsp;2606.27045 splits merge authority BY BLAST RADIUS (boundary/contract → HARD human;
                internal refactor → AUTO) and makes drift a blocking merge condition via a deterministic
                Intent-Graph-vs-Evidence-Graph diff — <em>but a single-author, unimplemented preprint</em></td>
            <td>Blueprint to adapt (not proof): #2563 Fork 1 + blast-radius, fused</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>The Productivity-Reliability Paradox</strong></td>
            <td>The most rigorous RCT (METR 2025) shows a <strong>19% slowdown</strong> for experienced devs on
                mature codebases; org telemetry shows a 98% PR jump alongside a 91% rise in review time, flat
                delivery</td>
            <td>Raw agent throughput inflates review cost without improving delivery — invest in the contract
                gate + a keep-changes-small nudge, not a faster generator</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
