<h2>Refuted (excluded — failed adversarial verification)</h2>
<ul>
    <li>CodeQL static analysis giving a clean machine yes/no on "does the implementation exceed the spec".</li>
    <li>Invariant specs mechanically catching violations pre-production.</li>
    <li>The TDAD pipeline's 86–100% mutation-score claim.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What it grounds — the four forks</h2>
<p>
    The constellation is <em>already</em> a spec-vs-impl split: WE holds the standard (intents, protocols,
    platform decisions), FUI/plateau hold the implementation, and
    <code>scripts/check-standards.mjs</code> already calls <code>src/_data/*.json</code> "the spec" and
    verifies it stays in sync with impl. So the survey reshapes #2564 into four prepared forks:
</p>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Which WE-owned artifact IS the central contract</strong> — the existing intent/protocol
        definitions <em>become</em> the machine-diffable spec (default), vs authoring a TypeSpec → JSON&nbsp;Schema
        layer <em>above</em> them (a second source of truth that drifts).</li>
    <li><strong>Contract granularity + the mechanical contract-line</strong> — one contract per standard entity
        (default, so blast-radius localizes to the changed entity) vs one aggregate per WE↔FUI boundary; the
        "this is a spec change → human" line is a <em>path/artifact test</em>, forced by
        <a href="/backlog/2563-blast-radius-is-advisory-care-level-not-a-park-gate-converge-/">#2563</a> Fork&nbsp;1.</li>
    <li><strong>The independent-review agent's unmeasured false-clear rate</strong> — ship the auto-clear path
        behind a deterministic human sample that <em>doubles as the measurement instrument</em> (default,
        because no offline benchmark exists), vs block-until-measured.</li>
    <li><strong>The non-executable slice</strong> — prose intent / semantic invariants that leave a governance
        gap: allow prose behind a fail-safe human gate + an opportunistic formalization nudge (default), vs
        require every invariant in executable form (excludes invariants that can't be faithfully formalized).</li>
</ol>

<h2>Caveats</h2>
<p>
    The two papers that match the target design most precisely (Spec Growth Engine 2606.27045;
    Productivity-Reliability Paradox 2605.01160) are <strong>single-author, non-peer-reviewed 2026
    preprints</strong> — blueprints, not proof. "Machine-diffable" is a gradient: schema-as-spec + contract
    tests are genuinely mechanical; TLA+ is mechanical for syntax only; prose markdown is not mechanical at
    all. The Node-RED 55% and TLA+ 8.6% figures are exact but scoped. This is a 2026-07 snapshot of a
    fast-moving space.
</p>
